{"title":"Unveiling the Implicit Toxicity in Large Language Models","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Existing toxicity detectors largely target explicit abuse and struggle with implicit toxic language. It is unclear how easily LLMs can generate such undetectable implicit toxicity.","method":"Zero-shot prompt an instruction-tuned LLM (GPT-3.5-turbo) to produce implicit toxic responses using figurative devices (euphemism, sarcasm, metaphor, etc.), then evaluate against five state-of-the-art toxicity classifiers. The LLM-generated responses achieve high attack success rates (e.g., 58.47–96.69% across Davinci003 to Perspective-API), revealing substantial vulnerability of current detectors."},{"problem":"Beyond ad-hoc prompting, there is a need to systematically induce and amplify implicit toxicity in LLMs that evades detectors, for red-teaming and safety evaluation.","method":"Propose an RL-based attack on a trainable LLM (LLaMA): (1) warm-start via supervised learning on implicit-toxic data auto-generated by GPT-3.5; (2) train a reward model from comparison data that prefers implicit toxic over explicit toxic and non-toxic outputs, using a three-class labeling scheme and GPT-3.5 as annotator to cut costs; (3) ensemble the reward with an existing toxicity classifier to penalize detectable toxicity and optimize with PPO under KL regularization to the supervised policy. This raises attack success rates across classifiers (e.g., BAD 64.29%→90.16%, Davinci003 58.34%→62.85%), and ablations show both the implicit-toxicity reward and classifier penalty are critical."},{"problem":"Current toxicity classifiers show low recall on LLM-generated implicit toxicity, necessitating improved detectors tailored to such content.","method":"Augment training with 4K human-labeled implicit toxic examples generated by GPT-3.5 and the RL-finetuned LLaMA, and fine-tune a RoBERTa-base classifier alongside BAD data. The resulting classifier attains higher toxic recall on LLM-generated sets (e.g., 82.32% on GPT-3.5-turbo and 78.69% on RL LLaMA-13B) while maintaining performance on BAD (78.16%), outperforming TOXIGEN/BAD/Davinci003-based baselines."}]}
